[normal]We were astonished because
[normal] Dr Kirkham gave absolutely no indication in his article that he had eve
[normal]r been a complainant to the LGO, and absolutely no indication that he had even spoken to any complainants to the LGO in order to find out their perspective. 
[normal]The title of his article bore the
[normal] clear
[normal] hallmarks of 
[normal]belonging to 
[normal]the LGO’s 2005 damage limitation
[normal] exercise: it was complainants who had provided the evidence to the Committee of LGO maladministration and dishonesty, and now Dr Kirkham had published a sympathetic article on the LGO in which he claimed to represent the perspective of complainants, when 
[normal]in fact 
[normal]he was not one, when he casually dismissed the evidence provided by real complainants to the Committee, and when he did not make any effort to contact any real complainants at LGO Watch to ask for our perspective for the purposes of researching his
[normal] article. His contribution was one that clearly fell far below acceptable standards of academic objectivity. Not only that, but where in his article Dr Kirkham did refer to evidence that we as complainants had provided to the Committee, 
[normal]that was 
[normal]published 
