[normal]Dr Kirkham makes another controversial statement on page 392:
[normal]“[...] the LGO are there to perform a number of roles and, of those roles, publi
[normal]cly calling local authorities to account is one of the least important.” 
[normal]I am not convinced that the taxpayers who fund the LGO would have much sympathy for Dr Kirkham’s position on this matter. Surely one of the greatest checks and balances
[normal] on the behavi
[normal]our of a public authority, or of any person in public life, is the possibility of being publicly called to account. This is surely the essence of “accountability”. Admittedly, the priority of the LGO should be to provide a remedy for a complainant who has 
[normal]suffered maladministration with significant injustice and harm at the hands of his local authority. But to suggest that calling local authorities to account for maladministration should be “
[normal]one of the least important roles”
